    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey so im doing a lot of hiit lately and my legs feel like they are burning like crazy during the sprints. can u explain what is actually happening with the lactic acid in my muscles when that happens? and how does my body get rid of it after i stop?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "During HIIT, your legs are depleted of energy stores in the form of ATP (adenosine triphosphate), forcing your body to break down stored carbohydrates and release lactate, a byproduct of glycolysis. This buildup of lactic acid in your muscles causes the burning sensation you're experiencing. As a result of this storage, your muscle cells can't function normally, leading to the intense pain. Once you stop exercising, your body initially stores lactic acid in your muscle cells and liver, then you'll need 24-48 hours for it to break down and be fully eliminated.",
      "source": "target",
