    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense but it sounds a bit overwhelming. so basically these molecules just start piling up in my legs and causing pain? is there a way to describe how they actually interact with the muscle cells to cause that \"burn\" sensation? like what are they actually doing to the tissue?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Lactic acid molecules interact with the muscle cells by binding to ion channels and receptors, altering the way they function and communicate with other cells. Specifically, lactic acid blocks the removal of key ions such as potassium and calcium, disrupting the normal electrical signals that allow muscles to contract and relax. This results in a buildup of an excessive amount of sodium and calcium, leading to muscle cell depolarization and the sensation of burning, fatigue, and discomfort.",
      "source": "target",
